The paper proposes a method for measuring and discovering correlations in categorical data, which is a common task in machine learning and data science. The use of a non-parametric measure and an algorithmic framework suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG). The focus on efficient discovery of top-k correlated sets suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The use of non-parametric measures and the focus on interpretability suggest that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI). The use of bounding functions and the focus on optimization outcomes suggest that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Information Theory (cs.IT). Finally, the empirical evaluation and case studies suggest that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI).
